&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Intake Paralegal&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Pro Bono&amp;nbsp;Services&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;LSNYC’s&amp;nbsp;Pro Bono Program&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;LSNYC’s pro bono program engages a range of private partners on behalf of thousands of low-income New Yorkers across multiple practice areas. Managed by a director and staffed by two deputy directors, three immigration coordinating attorneys, a bankruptcy attorney, three housing/public benefits coordinating attorneys, a LGBTQ+ advocacy coordinating attorney, and five paralegals, the Pro Bono Services Department (“Department”) works with LSNYC staff and pro bono partners to create and manage pro bono projects, place cases, run clinics, train and mentor volunteers, access in-kind resources, and match individual volunteers with appropriate LSNYC offices. LSNYC’s private partners include more than 125 law firms and corporations, along with law schools, bar associations, and individual volunteers.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our pro bono program offers more than a dozen initiatives focused on housing, immigration, benefits, name change, education, family, and more. LSNYC conducts more than 100 pro bono clinics and study groups each year for tenants, immigrants, and transgender clients, among others. Immigration makes up more than half of our pro bono work, with a focus on asylum, VAWA self-petitions, battered spouse waivers, removal defense, habeas corpus petitions, and naturalizations. We operate a high-volume practice, with more than 5,000 pro bono cases annually.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Opportunity&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Paralegal for the Pro Bono Department will work to expand and operate our benefits, housing, immigration, and name change clinics and case placement, and to support additional pro bono efforts with corporations and law firms. Collectively, these initiatives will help thousands of New Yorkers who need legal representation to secure safe housing, improved immigration status, and other forms of relief.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
